<paragraph id="8B8436D8FFD02A2EFF71FA7FFC23F93C" blockId="20.[160,1156,1461,1727]" pageId="20" pageNumber="1408">
This genus includes 30 species from various parts of the world, but the majority of them were described from the Old World (
<bibRefCitation id="EFAA4B29FFD02A2EFD9BFA1DFC90FA6C" author="Mound LA &amp; Minaei K" box="[586,870,1495,1519]" pageId="20" pageNumber="1408" pagination="2919 - 2978" refId="ref9815" refString="Mound LA, Minaei K. 2007. Australian thrips of the Haplothrips lineage (Insecta: Thysanoptera). J Nat Hist. 41: 2919 - 2978." type="journal article" year="2007">Mound and Minaei 2007</bibRefCitation>
). Members of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3B4D5BFFD02A2EFBDEFA1DFB75FA6C" authorityName="Hood" authorityYear="1913" box="[1039,1155,1495,1519]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Podothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="1408" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94FEACAFFD02A2EFBDEFA1DFB75FA6C" box="[1039,1155,1495,1519]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="1408">Podothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have prosternal basantra unusually longer than wide, enlarged fore femora, and fore tarsi bearing a tooth (sometimes also a tooth at the apex of the fore tibia) (
<bibRefCitation id="EFAA4B29FFD02A2EFC3AF9D7FB80F9B6" author="Ritchie JM" box="[1003,1142,1565,1589]" pageId="20" pageNumber="1408" pagination="261 - 282" refId="ref10002" refString="Ritchie JM. 1975. A revision of the grass-living genus Podothrips (Thysanoptera: Phlaeothripidae). J Entomol (B). 43: 261 - 282." type="journal article" year="1975">Ritchie 1975</bibRefCitation>
). This genus might be related to 
<taxonomicName id="4C3B4D5BFFD02A2EFDD3F9F5FD76F9D4" baseAuthorityName="Mound and Marullo" baseAuthorityYear="1996" box="[514,640,1599,1623]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Haplothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="1408" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94FEACAFFD02A2EFDD3F9F5FD76F9D4" box="[514,640,1599,1623]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="1408">Haplothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and most species seem to be predaceous on scale insects in 
<taxonomicName id="4C3B4D5BFFD02A2EFE89F9A8FE4EF9F9" authorityName="Barnhart" authorityYear="1895" baseAuthorityName="R.Br." box="[344,440,1634,1658]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="20" pageNumber="1408" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Poaceae</taxonomicName>
. Only three 
<taxonomicName id="4C3B4D5BFFD02A2EFD98F9A8FCEFF9F9" box="[585,793,1634,1658]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Podothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="1408" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B94FEACAFFD02A2EFD98F9A8FD4BF9F9" box="[585,701,1634,1658]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="1408">Podothrips</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
are reported from Central and South America, two originally described from 
<collectingCountry id="F32C7648FFD02A2EFD7BF94FFD10F91E" box="[682,742,1669,1693]" name="Brazil" pageId="20" pageNumber="1408">Brazil</collectingCountry>
and one from 
<collectingCountry id="F32C7648FFD02A2EFC43F94FFBE5F91E" box="[914,1043,1669,1693]" name="Puerto Rico" pageId="20" pageNumber="1408">Puerto Rico</collectingCountry>
(
<tableCitation id="C6B90363FFD02A2EFBF2F94FFB80F91E" box="[1059,1142,1669,1693]" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="3.[160,216,406,429]" captionText="Table 1. Haplothripini species (Insecta: Thysanoptera) recorded from Central and South America." pageId="20" pageNumber="1408">Table 1</tableCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAA4B29FFD02A2EFF71F96DFE27F93C" author="Mound LA &amp; Marullo R" box="[160,465,1703,1727]" pageId="20" pageNumber="1408" pagination="1 - 488" refId="ref9785" refString="Mound LA, Marullo R. 1996. The Thrips of Central and South America: an Introduction. Mem Entomol, Int. 6: 1 - 488." type="journal article" year="1996">Mound and Marullo (1996)</bibRefCitation>
provided a key to these Neotropical species.
</paragraph>
